06570nam a22008175i 9780823291731DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232917317 a10.1515/97808232917312doi  a(DE-B1597)565987  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0000002bisacsh1 aHanegraaff, Wouter J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHidden Intercourse :bEros and Sexuality in the History of Western Esotericism /cWouter J. Hanegraaff, Jeffrey J. Kripal. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (568 p.) :b9 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Things We Do Not Talk About -- tSexuality and Sexual Symbolism in Hermetic and Gnostic Thought and Practice (Second–Fourth Centuries) -- tConceiving Spirits: The Mystery of Valentinian Sex -- tSexual Intercourse Between Humans and Demons in the Islamic Tradition -- tMurmuring Secrets: Eroticism and Esotericism in Medieval Kabbalah -- tTa'anug: Erotic Delights from Kabbalah to Hasidism -- tComplications of Eros: The Song of Songs in John of Morigny’s Liber fl orum celestis Doctrine -- tUnder the Mantle of Love: The Mystical Eroticisms of Marsilio Ficino and Giordano Bruno -- tRevealing Analogies: The Descriptive and Deceptive Roles of Sexuality and Gender in Latin Alchemy -- tProbing Women and Penetrating Witchcraft in Early Modern Europe -- tSensuous Relation with Sophia in Christian Theosophy -- tDeadly Dates: Bodies and Sex in Spiritualist Heave -- tSexual Mysticisms in Nineteenth Century America: John Humphrey Noyes, Thomas Lake Harris, and Alice Bunker Stockham -- tPaschal Beverly Randolph and Sexual Magic -- tThe Knight of Spermatophagy: Penetrating the Mysteries of Georges Le Clément de Saint-Marcq -- tThe Yoga of Sex: Tantra, Orientalism, and Sex Magic in the Ordo Templi Orientis -- tThe Theory and Practice of Sexual Magic, Exemplified by Four Magical Groups in the Early Twentieth Century -- tThe Roar of Awakening: The Eros of Esalen and the Western Transmission of Tantra -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Persons -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom rumors about gnostic orgies in antiquity to the explicit erotic symbolism of alchemical texts, from the subtly coded eroticism of medieval kabbalah to the sexual magic practiced by contemporary occultists and countercultural translations of Asian Tantra, the history of Western esotericism is rich in references to the domains of eros and sexuality. This volume, which brings together an impressive array of top-level specialists, is the first to analyze the eroticism of the esoteric without sensationalism or cheap generalizations, but on the basis of expert scholarship and attention to textual and historical detail. While there are few domains where the imagination may so easily run wild, the various contributions seek to distinguish fact from fiction—only to find that historical realities are sometimes even stranger than the fantasies. In doing so, they reveal the outlines of a largely unknown history spanning more than twenty centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aBroek, Roelof van den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoudert, Allison P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeConick, April D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeveney, John Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaivre, Antoine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 